title: For Sale:  Colt 1911 Pistol - Blued - .45 ACP - Limited WW1 Reproduction
postcontent:
Hi, 

For sale is a "used as new" condition Colt 1911 WW1 reproduction pistol. This is the 01918 Black Army Oxide edition of the WW1 reproduction. This is a late model of the production run of this series, in the 3,7xx range of just over 4,000 pistols made. While there was a recall on the safety catch of the early versions, this one was not recalled, and has the correct metallurgy used in all parts. The gun is blued with the black oxide finish typical of the US Army issued 1911s during the First World War. Bluing is of high order, typical of Colt outstanding 1911 pistols. Compare to the very nice but less pretty parkerized WW2 reproduction pistol.  

It has the early notch GI-style front and rear sights. 

I have put just under 150 rounds of .45 ACP through the gun. The cosmetic condition is 99%, with only some slight finish marks on the hammer face and the barrel, both of which are similarly blued with the black oxide. The gun came this way when I got it, the result of the slide being wracked for the purpose of demonstration and safety checks. 

A really great 1911. Over the years since these repro's finished production (around 2010), their value has enhanced slightly, and like most Colt 1911s it holds value significantly even after use. It feeds flawlessly, is amazingly accurate, and the WW1 guns are especially valued as utterly faithful tributes to the original guns, the very first 1911 warhorses. A very beautiful shooter. 

Included is the new Colt manual, a reprint of the original 1911 manual, the original individual pistol box in 100% condition, Colt screwdriver / takedown punch tool, 2 blued Colt magazines, brown oiled wrapping paper for the gun and mags, and a large blue Colt custom shop box, with the the Colt emblem embossed on it. 

If you want a solid shooting, stylish and top-quality 1911, this Colt may be it. Price is $1100 USD. This will be a licensed FFL transaction. The price includes the fee for the background check / FFL transfer. I have a Milwaukee FFL picked out- If there are issues regarding FFL preferences, I am happy to work with individual buyers. Please email me with any questions. Thank you!

THE FIRST ONE WITH CASH TAKES IT!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!

I bought this about half a year ago, I don't know how many rounds went through it but I know I only put around 80 rounds through it. The firearm is cleaned ritually even if it has not been shot. I've took really good care of it while I had it! I don't have time to go out shooting anymore so I would like to try to get rid of it. 

The Smith & Wesson SW99 is a modern, polymer frame pistol that is nearly identical to the Walther P99. The SW99 features an internal striker, as opposed to the classical external hammer. It is chambered in .40 S&W. The pistol lacks a manual safety; instead a de-cocking button is placed on the top rear section of the slide, which when actuated, places the firearm into double-action mode. This mechanism differs with each variation of the action, which will be explained below. The SW99 features several safety features including a loaded chamber indicator on the right side of the slide, a protruding, red-painted cocking indicator, and a drop safety. As with the P99, the cocking indicator does not protrude from the slide of the QA variant unless the weapon is fired, as it is in a constant partially cocked state. The SW99 also features a fully supported chamber design, which leaves no portion of the chambered round exposed. Because of this there is less chance of injury to the shooter and/or destruction of the pistol, should the casing head rupture.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Information about the Law...
location: all over, Winston Salem, North Carolina
postcontent:
Here is a little information about the Laws in the USA about Handgun Sales, 
Person - To - Person, that Do Not Involve Dealers...

I'm just saying, CCH and Purchasing Permits are NOT required as of right now
for a Person - To - Person Transaction, there are so many people out here that
just Don't know the Laws. We have Bought and Sold Guns most of my life, and it is such a pain now to make a deal, because people just don't know what the laws really are...

http://smartgunlaws.org/private-sales-policy-summary/

The Gun Control Act of 1968 provides that persons “engaged in the business” of dealing in firearms must be licensed.3 Although Congress did not originally define the term “engaged in the business,” it did so in 1986 as part of the McClure-Volkmer Act (also known as the “Firearms Owners’ Protection Act”). That Act defined the term “engaged in the business,” as applied to a firearms dealer, as “a person who devotes time, attention, and labor to dealing in firearms as a regular course of trade or business with the principal objective of livelihood and profit through the repetitive purchase and resale of firearms.”4
Significantly, however, the term was defined to exclude a person who “makes occasional sales, exchanges, or purchases of firearms for the enhancement of a personal collection or for a hobby, or who sells all or part of his personal collection of firearms.”

5.
Consequently, unlicensed sellers may sell firearms without conducting background checks or documenting the transaction in any way. In addition, because federal law does not require private sellers to inspect a buyer’s driver’s license or any other identification, there is no obligation for such sellers to confirm that a buyer is of legal age to purchase a firearm. 
As a result, convicted felons, minors and other prohibited purchasers can easily buy guns from unlicensed sellers.

title: For Trade:  Sig P238 with night sights 4 mags, ammo, 3 holsters
postcontent:
I am reluctantly putting my sig p238 up for trade.  This gun was purchased 1 year ago.  It has been carried a lot, but shot relatively little.  It is the HD model with rosewood grips and night sights.  This gun is reliable super concealable and very accurate for its size.  I have no problem putting an entire magazine worth of shots on an 8.5 x 11 target at 25 yards.  The only reason I am getting rid of this gun is that it is not the cheapest gun to shoot.  I would like to get something small and easily concealable and something a little more fun to put a lot of rounds through.  

My gun will come with the following:  

Sig p238 HD w/ night sights $650 with box paper work and original sig holster and 6rd mag
1 extra sig 7rd mag $50
1 extra 7rd colt mag (works fine with gun) $35
1 pro mag 6rd mag $25
1 desantis leather iwb holster $36
1 custom owb pancake style leather holster $50
3 boxes of buffalo bore +p defensive ammo (plus 2 mags worth of extra) $99
6 boxes of winchester 100 rd white box fmj $216
6 boxes of federal 50 rd fmj$120
1 box of remington umc 50rd fmj $18
That adds up to an original package value of $1300 plus tax.  I would want your trade to be worth the same (in original retail value) or make up for it in cash.  I know what some people are asking for right now and I refuse to play those games.   Your xd is not worth $700.  If your trade includes a .380 I would keep some of my ammo and adjust trade value accordingly.

This trade will be a package deal and to be clear, I am not interested in trading for any weapon that does not come with at least some ammo.  Ideally I would like something like a keltec .380 or lcp or pocket sized 9mm and a fullsize 9mm.  I may also be interested in a single stack 9mm like a shield 9 or kahr 9mm.  I would also be interested in a trade for a weapon plus cash on either your end or my end.  I am most interested in the following larger 9mm handguns: Springfield xd9 or xd9sc, m&p 9 or compact version, glock 26 or 19, sig 226, sig sp2022.  If your trade involves a single stack 9mm or dependable .380 I would be interested in that plus a big game hunting rifle. 

Send me any trade offers via email along with contact info and I will get back to you.
